<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06018151 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06018151 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  RADIO; SHOW; MIDEAST; WAR; IRAQ  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  At KCBS-AM (740) on Thursday afternoon, director of news and programming EdCavagnaro was heading into his second day of &quot;wall-to-wall&quot; -- the term radioofficials use for all-news coverage -- and thinking about easing a fewcommercials back into the mix. Then he got the CBS network news that missileshad hit Tel Aviv.;    &quot;This puts a totally new twist on everything,&quot; he said.&quot;We'll be wall-to-wall now until . . . &quot; his voice trailed off.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  GULF NEWS AND TALK DOMINATE RADIO DIAL  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  WAR IN THE GULFSee also related stories on pages 1A-12A of this section.  </MEMO><TEXT>     All across the dial, local news stations, and some stations where newsusually means headlines at the top of the hour, dropped weather, sports, talkshows and commercials in favor of a continuous combination of network reportsand local news from their own staff.;    Talk-show lines jammed;  At KGO-AM(810), a San Francisco station owned and operated by ABC, news director JohnMcConnell had decided around 2:15 p.m. Thursday to let his station inch backinto its news-and-talk-show format. Talk-show host Jim Eason took calls fromthe station's jammed lines, until KGO went back to its network coverage afterthe Iraqi missiles hit.;    &quot;The lines have been lit up even though we haven'tbeen taking telephone calls,&quot; said McConnell. &quot;We haven't announced thetalk-show telephone numbers for 24 hours and they're all lit.&quot;;    For moststations, the wall-to-wall coverage began around 4 p.m. Wednesday, just as thefirst Bay Area commuters started fiddling with their car radios. At 4:06 p.m.,KNBR-AM (680) program director Bob Agnew cut away from the Golden StateWarriors basketball game.;    'It was the real thing';  &quot;We'd decided we'dplay it by ear and break into the game if it was the real thing, and it becameapparent that it was the real thing,&quot; said Agnew, whose NBC affiliate stationis known for its sports coverage.;    On the FM side, National Public Radio,the Washington-based service heard on KQED-FM (88.5), KCSM-FM (91.1), KALW-FM(91.7) and KUSP-FM (89.0), expanded both its morning and evening news shows byseveral hours, and opened its lines for nationwide call-in shows between 11a.m. and 1 p.m.;    And volunteer and staff reporters at independent stationKPFA-FM (94.10), known for offering left-leaning commentary, continuedinterviewing a mix of peace activists and taking live reports from peacedemonstrations.;    &quot;Are you kidding?&quot; said program director Melanie Berzon,when asked if listeners were calling the station. &quot;We have very vocallisteners normally, and at a time like this, it's very intense.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  KATHLEEN DONNELLY, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910118  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  440  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday January 18, 199100018151,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>